WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
So I get to talk about our problem child and not have to not talk about the cure word or anything

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:10.500
like that. But I'm going to talk about the biology and the differences in extramedullary disease.

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:16.920
And when we talk about plasmacytomas in myeloma, we always, I see the good, the bad, and the ugly.

00:00:17.100 --> 00:00:21.600
So the good is those who don't have plasmacytomas. Bad are those who have

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:27.700
perimedullary plasmacytomas. And the ugly cases and are hard, like hard to treat patients are

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:33.220
the extramedullary disease. And truly extramedullary disease with a plasmacytoma is not attached to the

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:39.500
bone, but it's only in soft tissue. And why is this our headache? When we look at data, even with

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:44.760
the newest agents that we have, like CAR-T and bispecific T-cell engagers, we see that CAR-T and

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:49.480
T-cell and bispecifics are suboptimal in terms of the responses that we're obtaining. At Mount

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:56.420
Sinai, we did a study with 134 patients with relapse disease who received CAR-T. And we saw

00:00:56.420 --> 00:00:57.460
out of those 34%.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:04.040
And 34 of those patients had extramedullary disease, 25 had perimedullary disease. And then

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:08.200
we looked at the response rate, we looked at the median progression-free survival and overall

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:15.160
survival. And we see that it's the extramedullary disease that really had the poor median PFS and

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:21.240
the poor overall survival. Those who had perimedullary disease or periskeletal disease

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:27.540
had a better PFS and overall survival and somewhat similar to those who did not have

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:34.880
any plasmasytomas. The other thing that we identified is that the tumor burden also

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:39.880
correlated with poorer outcomes. And the bigger the tumor burden, more than 50 centimeters

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:47.840
squared, that's when we saw the biggest impact in overall response rates and depth of response

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:55.780
with overall response rates of 57% versus those with small tumor burden of 81% and complete

00:01:55.780 --> 00:01:57.240
response rates of 0%.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:03.040
With heavy tumor burden and extramedullary disease. The other interesting thing is it's

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:11.700
not just the patients who have extramedullary disease at diagnosis or prior to starting therapy

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:16.200
that are going to have poorer outcomes. But the thing that we're seeing is that with these

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:21.640
new novel immunotherapies, both CAR-T and bispecifics, we're having a higher trend of

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:26.880
relapsing with extramedullary disease. So are we actually changing the biology of this

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:26.880
relapse?

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:32.420
Or are we just dealing with patients who have been heavily pretreated and who already were

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:36.980
destined to have all these mutations and we're just seeing the outcome of that progression?

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:42.640
When it comes to bispecifics, we see the same thing. Across the board, all of the bispecifics

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:48.260
are having suboptimal responses to patients who have true extramedullary disease. And

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:52.440
we see that these patients, they do better than conventional chemotherapy, but they still

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:57.700
have a suboptimal response. But what is leading to these suboptimal responses? And we see

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:03.860
that there's a genomic complexity in those patients that have extramedullary disease. And

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:09.780
the Mayo Clinic evaluated patients, and they did bone marrow aspirates, and they also did biopsies

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:13.940
of the extramedullary disease. They had six patients where they did these two samples

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:20.100
at the same time. The rest were at different time points. But we see that there is a clonal gene

00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:26.340
mutation that is much higher in the extramedullary disease compared to the bone marrow aspiration. We

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:27.620
see a significant increase in the bone marrow aspiration. And we see that there is a significant

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:36.900
higher amount of tumor mutations compared to the bone marrow aspirate. And when we look at the

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:42.180
extramedullary disease, there really isn't any real significant difference in extramedullary

00:03:42.180 --> 00:03:49.780
disease that is front line or after relapse or secondary. So it's as a class or as a group,

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:53.460
that extramedullary disease is behaving differently. And we should consider

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:57.540
this as a complete, by the way, as a completely different disease, but it is definitely a

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:02.340
different beast. And it's not a regular myeloma. We should have a classification for patients who

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:08.100
have true extramedullary disease. We also see that in order for myeloma cells to survive outside of

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:12.100
the bone marrow, they need to have independence of all the nutrients that are in the bone marrow

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:20.500
microenvironment. And we see that there are cell adhesion genes, alterations in these genes that

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:27.460
are overexpressed in extramedullary disease samples compared to bone marrow, where we see genes as

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:36.820
associated to cell adhesions like ROBO1, ROBO2, and FAT1 that are overexpressed and seen in up to 25%

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:42.820
of these extramedullary disease samples compared to less than 5% when we take a sample from the bone

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:50.980
marrow aspirate. And ROBO1 in particular also correlates with MMZ, which is translocation 414,

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:56.260
which is frequently associated with development of extramedullary disease in myeloma patients.

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:57.380
Now, there's been a multiple

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:03.220
studies that are identifying or studying particular alterations and gene expressions.

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:09.220
There's CD56 expression that is suggested to be also a contributing factor to survival outside

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:15.780
of the bone marrow, reduction of CXCR4 expression, and CD44 YALRA9 expression.

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:21.540
So, more to come. We need to understand these more. Is it a combination of these or is there

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:27.300
one particular that is actually causing these extramedullary disease survival? I would say that

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:33.300
this might be a combination because if we're seeing just 25% alteration in these samples,

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:37.620
that means that there's something else that's additive to make these cells survive outside

00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:41.700
of the bone marrow. But we also have a dysfunctional immune microenvironment in

00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:49.060
these extramedullary lesions. And when we sample these tumors, we see that there's reduced effector

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:56.980
tumor ratio, there's fewer CD4 T cells, there's more exhausted CD8 cells, and there's an enriched

00:05:57.220 --> 00:06:04.260
CD16 negative NK cell population. In the areas where we see plasma cells, we see that there's

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:12.660
more exhausted TIM3 PD1 T cells in the areas of the plasmacytoma or extramedullary disease that

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:17.700
does not contain plasma cells, but it's more stroma. Then in those areas, we do see more

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:27.140
activated CD8 positive T cells and M1 macrophages. So, we're seeing different cells and components with

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:33.300
in the plasmacytoma, and it tends to be associated whether there's myeloma cells around it or not.

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:38.980
And we need to understand this better to be able to identify what is causing these changes in this

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:45.540
extramedullary disease, what's the microenvironment stimulation that's making these immune

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:51.060
compartments be very differently within the same extramedullary disease. And then just to summarize

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:56.500
and to keep with time, unlike my previous speakers, extramedullary disease should be considered

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:01.620
an aggressive and distinct variant of myeloma. We should have a special classification for

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:05.780
these population, and it has unique characteristics, marrow independence,

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:10.580
higher genomic complexity, pronounced clonal divergence, more dysfunctional immune

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:16.500
microenvironment. And as we learn and understand this better, then we can identify potential

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:21.620
targeted ways of treating this disease better. But at the same time, now that we're seeing,

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:26.980
for example, with redirect one, that we have a better response, what is causing this

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:33.700
additive effect of BCMA and GPRC5D that is helping overcome this so that we can start to tackle these

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:39.220
potential areas of niches that we can treat. And with that, I thank you for your attention.
